00:23:19.590 --> 00:23:22.433
But for everyone else who
hasn't heard of content

00:23:22.433 --> 00:23:24.360
security policy, it basically--
it's a set of

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:27.050
directives that you can include
in your HTTP headers

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:30.950
on the response back that
indicate essentially what type

00:23:30.950 --> 00:23:33.730
of domains that requests can
come from from the site.

00:23:33.730 --> 00:23:36.570
It's essentially there to
mitigate cross site scripting.

00:23:36.570 --> 00:23:38.960
So you can basically say,
I don't allow scripts--

00:23:38.960 --> 00:23:40.700
I only want to allow scripts
from my domain.

00:23:40.700 --> 00:23:43.600
I don't want to allow scripts
from any other site.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:44.780
And I don't want
to allow eval.

00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:47.140
I don't want to allow
new function.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:49.260
I don't want to allow any
inline script, as well.

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:51.340
Because inline script's
an interesting one.

00:23:51.340 --> 00:23:53.950
If someone can inject a script
tag into your page, well, they

00:23:53.950 --> 00:23:55.490
can cross site script
your page.

00:23:55.490 --> 00:23:57.570
And the idea behind content
security policy is you can

00:23:57.570 --> 00:23:58.710
actually turn that
feature off.

00:23:58.710 --> 00:24:00.760
So you can say, people can't--

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:03.970
basically, they might be able
to insert a script.

00:24:03.970 --> 00:24:06.560
But they can't insert any old
piece of JavaScript that they

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:08.510
choose to execute themselves.

00:24:08.510 --> 00:24:10.215
